  {'type': 'string_type', 'loc': ('response', 'items', 3), 'msg': 'Input should be a valid string', 'input': {'_id': '69ad4e3b773afa9e25b39372', 'movie_id': '1236153', 'content_type': 'movie', 'movie_title': 'Mercy', 'movie_poster_url': 'https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/original/pyok1kZJCfyuFapYXzHcy7BLlQa.jpg', 'status': 'published', 'slug': 'mercy', 'overall_rating': 6.41, 'verdict': 'Average', 'summary': 'The Courtroom Just Became A Battlefield', 'content': 'Mercy is the kind of film that looks more promising on paper than it ever feels on screen. The premise has enough intrigue to pull you in initially, and the opening does just enough to suggest something engaging is coming, but the film quickly settles into a predictable and emotionally flat rhythm. The screenplay keeps things moving but lacks sharpness, with dialogues that feel functional rather than memorable. Direction is competent without ever elevating the material, and while the lead performances are serviceable, they don’t carry enough weight to make the story resonate. Visually, the film holds up better, with clean cinematography and solid technical execution, but that only highlights the gap between how it looks and how it feels. The thematic layer is present but underdeveloped, never fully explored in a way that leaves a lasting impact. By the end, it doesn’t fail outright, but it doesn’t succeed in any meaningful way either. It’s watchable, occasionally engaging, but ultimately forgettable, landing squarely in that frustrating middle ground where nothing is bad enough to criticize heavily, yet nothing is strong enough to remember.', 'spoiler_section': None, 'cast_performances': '', 'director_trademarks': '', 'viewing_context': 'Family? Yes. \nKids? Yes.', 'trivia_and_details': '', 'favourite_dialogues': [], 'cinematic_moments': [], 'aspects': {'story': {'score': 6.7, 'comment': ''}, 'screenplay': {'score': 6.6, 'comment': ''}, 'originality': {'score': 6.5, 'comment': ''}, 'opening': {'score': 7.0, 'commen